<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-220-230 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 371 184</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Feb 18 1991 v8 n7 p33(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC urged to postpone rule about satellite competition: State,Commerce ask agency to weigh implications. (Federal CommunicationsCommission)(International Networks)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Messmer, Ellen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Departments of Commerce and State are requesting that theFederal Communications Commission (FCC) postpone a decision on apetition issued by Pan American Satellite Corp (PANAMSAT)regarding a change in the rules controlling internationalsatellite competition.andP;  The petition proposes the lifting of a banpreventing PANAMSAT from having its international satelliteservices linked to the public switched network.andP;  This would endthe International Telecommunications Satellite Organization's(INTELSAT) monopoly on global public switched satellite traffic.andO;The Commerce and State departments want the matter to be put onhold until the Bush administration gives its position on theissue, which is expected to be sometime before May 1991.andP;  Analystssay it is likely the FCC will comply with the request for thedelay, although the FCC has yet to announce its answer.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Pan American Satellite Corp. (Services)Communications Satellite Corp. INTELSAT Satellite Services(Services).andO;Ticker:    CQ.andO;Topic:     United States. Department of StateUnited States. Department of CommerceUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionSatellite CarriersMonopoliesCompetitionInternational CommunicationsSatellite Communications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>